{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Metaphor lives a secret life all around us."},{"time":4000,"text":"We utter about six metaphors a minute."},{"time":8000,"text":"Metaphorical thinking is essential"},{"time":10000,"text":"to how we understand ourselves and others,"},{"time":13000,"text":"how we communicate, learn, discover"},{"time":16000,"text":"and invent."},{"time":18000,"text":"But metaphor is a way of thought before it is a way with words."}]},{"cues":[{"time":23000,"text":"Now, to assist me in explaining this,"},{"time":26000,"text":"I've enlisted the help of one of our greatest philosophers,"},{"time":29000,"text":"the reigning king of the metaphorians,"},{"time":33000,"text":"a man whose contributions to the field"},{"time":35000,"text":"are so great that he himself"},{"time":38000,"text":"has become a metaphor."},{"time":40000,"text":"I am, of course, referring to none other"},{"time":44000,"text":"than Elvis Presley."},{"time":46000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":47000,"text":"Now, \"All Shook Up\" is a great love song."},{"time":50000,"text":"It's also a great example of how"},{"time":52000,"text":"whenever we deal with anything abstract --"},{"time":54000,"text":"ideas, emotions, feelings, concepts, thoughts --"},{"time":58000,"text":"we inevitably resort to metaphor."},{"time":60000,"text":"In \"All Shook Up,\" a touch is not a touch, but a chill."},{"time":65000,"text":"Lips are not lips, but volcanoes."},{"time":68000,"text":"She is not she, but a buttercup."},{"time":71000,"text":"And love is not love, but being all shook up."}]},{"cues":[{"time":76000,"text":"In this, Elvis is following Aristotle's classic definition of metaphor"},{"time":80000,"text":"as the process of giving the thing"},{"time":83000,"text":"a name that belongs to something else."},{"time":86000,"text":"This is the mathematics of metaphor."},{"time":89000,"text":"And fortunately it's very simple."},{"time":91000,"text":"X equals Y."},{"time":93000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":96000,"text":"This formula works wherever metaphor is present."}]},{"cues":[{"time":99000,"text":"Elvis uses it, but so does Shakespeare"},{"time":102000,"text":"in this famous line from \"Romeo and Juliet:\""},{"time":104000,"text":"Juliet is the sun."},{"time":107000,"text":"Now, here, Shakespeare gives the thing, Juliet,"},{"time":111000,"text":"a name that belongs to something else, the sun."},{"time":116000,"text":"But whenever we give a thing a name that belongs to something else,"},{"time":119000,"text":"we give it a whole network of analogies too."},{"time":122000,"text":"We mix and match what we know about the metaphor's source,"},{"time":125000,"text":"in this case the sun,"},{"time":127000,"text":"with what we know about its target, Juliet."},{"time":130000,"text":"And metaphor gives us a much more vivid understanding of Juliet"},{"time":133000,"text":"than if Shakespeare had literally described what she looks like."}]},{"cues":[{"time":138000,"text":"So, how do we make and understand metaphors?"},{"time":140000,"text":"This might look familiar."},{"time":142000,"text":"The first step is pattern recognition."},{"time":144000,"text":"Look at this image. What do you see?"},{"time":147000,"text":"Three wayward Pac-Men,"},{"time":149000,"text":"and three pointy brackets are actually present."},{"time":152000,"text":"What we see, however,"},{"time":154000,"text":"are two overlapping triangles."},{"time":156000,"text":"Metaphor is not just the detection of patterns;"},{"time":159000,"text":"it is the creation of patterns."},{"time":161000,"text":"Second step, conceptual synesthesia."}]},{"cues":[{"time":164000,"text":"Now, synesthesia is the experience of a stimulus in once sense organ"},{"time":169000,"text":"in another sense organ as well,"},{"time":171000,"text":"such as colored hearing."},{"time":173000,"text":"People with colored hearing"},{"time":175000,"text":"actually see colors when they hear the sounds"},{"time":178000,"text":"of words or letters."},{"time":180000,"text":"We all have synesthetic abilities."},{"time":182000,"text":"This is the Bouba/Kiki test."},{"time":185000,"text":"What you have to do is identify which of these shapes"},{"time":187000,"text":"is called Bouba, and which is called Kiki."},{"time":191000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":192000,"text":"If you are like 98 percent of other people,"},{"time":194000,"text":"you will identify the round, amoeboid shape as Bouba,"},{"time":198000,"text":"and the sharp, spiky one as Kiki."},{"time":201000,"text":"Can we do a quick show of hands?"},{"time":203000,"text":"Does that correspond?"},{"time":205000,"text":"Okay, I think 99.9 would about cover it."},{"time":209000,"text":"Why do we do that?"},{"time":211000,"text":"Because we instinctively find, or create,"},{"time":215000,"text":"a pattern between the round shape"},{"time":217000,"text":"and the round sound of Bouba,"},{"time":220000,"text":"and the spiky shape and the spiky sound of Kiki."}]},{"cues":[{"time":225000,"text":"And many of the metaphors we use everyday are synesthetic."},{"time":229000,"text":"Silence is sweet."},{"time":231000,"text":"Neckties are loud."},{"time":233000,"text":"Sexually attractive people are hot."},{"time":236000,"text":"Sexually unattractive people leave us cold."},{"time":239000,"text":"Metaphor creates a kind of conceptual synesthesia,"},{"time":242000,"text":"in which we understand one concept"},{"time":244000,"text":"in the context of another."}]},{"cues":[{"time":247000,"text":"Third step is cognitive dissonance."},{"time":249000,"text":"This is the Stroop test."},{"time":251000,"text":"What you need to do here is identify"},{"time":253000,"text":"as quickly as possible"},{"time":255000,"text":"the color of the ink in which these words are printed."},{"time":258000,"text":"You can take the test now."},{"time":262000,"text":"If you're like most people, you will experience"},{"time":264000,"text":"a moment of cognitive dissonance"},{"time":266000,"text":"when the name of the color"},{"time":269000,"text":"is printed in a differently colored ink."},{"time":271000,"text":"The test shows that we cannot ignore the literal meaning of words"},{"time":274000,"text":"even when the literal meaning gives the wrong answer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":277000,"text":"Stroop tests have been done with metaphor as well."},{"time":279000,"text":"The participants had to identify, as quickly as possible,"},{"time":283000,"text":"the literally false sentences."},{"time":285000,"text":"They took longer to reject metaphors as false"},{"time":288000,"text":"than they did to reject literally false sentences."},{"time":291000,"text":"Why? Because we cannot ignore"},{"time":294000,"text":"the metaphorical meaning of words either."}]},{"cues":[{"time":297000,"text":"One of the sentences was, \"Some jobs are jails.\""},{"time":300000,"text":"Now, unless you're a prison guard,"},{"time":303000,"text":"the sentence \"Some jobs are jails\" is literally false."},{"time":306000,"text":"Sadly, it's metaphorically true."},{"time":309000,"text":"And the metaphorical truth interferes with our ability"},{"time":312000,"text":"to identify it as literally false."},{"time":314000,"text":"Metaphor matters because"},{"time":316000,"text":"it's around us every day, all the time."},{"time":319000,"text":"Metaphor matters because it creates expectations."}]},{"cues":[{"time":322000,"text":"Pay careful attention the next time you read the financial news."},{"time":326000,"text":"Agent metaphors describe price movements"},{"time":328000,"text":"as the deliberate action of a living thing,"},{"time":330000,"text":"as in, \"The NASDAQ climbed higher.\""},{"time":334000,"text":"Object metaphors describe price movements"},{"time":337000,"text":"as non-living things,"},{"time":339000,"text":"as in, \"The Dow fell like a brick.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":342000,"text":"Researchers asked a group of people"},{"time":344000,"text":"to read a clutch of market commentaries,"},{"time":346000,"text":"and then predict the next day's price trend."},{"time":349000,"text":"Those exposed to agent metaphors"},{"time":351000,"text":"had higher expectations that price trends would continue."},{"time":354000,"text":"And they had those expectations because"},{"time":356000,"text":"agent metaphors imply the deliberate action"},{"time":359000,"text":"of a living thing pursuing a goal."},{"time":362000,"text":"If, for example, house prices"},{"time":364000,"text":"are routinely described as climbing and climbing,"},{"time":367000,"text":"higher and higher, people might naturally assume"},{"time":369000,"text":"that that rise is unstoppable."},{"time":371000,"text":"They may feel confident, say,"},{"time":373000,"text":"in taking out mortgages they really can't afford."},{"time":376000,"text":"That's a hypothetical example of course."},{"time":379000,"text":"But this is how metaphor misleads."}]},{"cues":[{"time":383000,"text":"Metaphor also matters because it influences decisions"},{"time":386000,"text":"by activating analogies."},{"time":389000,"text":"A group of students was told that a small democratic country"},{"time":391000,"text":"had been invaded and had asked the U.S. for help."},{"time":394000,"text":"And they had to make a decision."},{"time":396000,"text":"What should they do?"},{"time":398000,"text":"Intervene, appeal to the U.N., or do nothing?"},{"time":401000,"text":"They were each then given one of three"},{"time":403000,"text":"descriptions of this hypothetical crisis."},{"time":405000,"text":"Each of which was designed to trigger"},{"time":408000,"text":"a different historical analogy:"},{"time":410000,"text":"World War II, Vietnam,"},{"time":412000,"text":"and the third was historically neutral."}]},{"cues":[{"time":415000,"text":"Those exposed to the World War II scenario"},{"time":417000,"text":"made more interventionist recommendations"},{"time":419000,"text":"than the others."},{"time":421000,"text":"Just as we cannot ignore the literal meaning of words,"},{"time":424000,"text":"we cannot ignore the analogies"},{"time":426000,"text":"that are triggered by metaphor."},{"time":430000,"text":"Metaphor matters because it opens the door to discovery."},{"time":433000,"text":"Whenever we solve a problem, or make a discovery,"},{"time":436000,"text":"we compare what we know with what we don't know."},{"time":439000,"text":"And the only way to find out about the latter"},{"time":441000,"text":"is to investigate the ways it might be like the former."}]},{"cues":[{"time":445000,"text":"Einstein described his scientific method as combinatory play."},{"time":449000,"text":"He famously used thought experiments,"},{"time":451000,"text":"which are essentially elaborate analogies,"},{"time":454000,"text":"to come up with some of his greatest discoveries."},{"time":457000,"text":"By bringing together what we know"},{"time":459000,"text":"and what we don't know through analogy,"},{"time":461000,"text":"metaphorical thinking strikes the spark"},{"time":463000,"text":"that ignites discovery."}]},{"cues":[{"time":467000,"text":"Now metaphor is ubiquitous, yet it's hidden."},{"time":471000,"text":"But you just have to look at the words around you"},{"time":474000,"text":"and you'll find it."},{"time":476000,"text":"Ralph Waldo Emerson described language"},{"time":478000,"text":"as \"fossil poetry.\""},{"time":480000,"text":"But before it was fossil poetry"},{"time":482000,"text":"language was fossil metaphor."},{"time":485000,"text":"And these fossils still breathe."}]},{"cues":[{"time":488000,"text":"Take the three most famous words in all of Western philosophy:"},{"time":493000,"text":"\"Cogito ergo sum.\""},{"time":495000,"text":"That's routinely translated as, \"I think, therefore I am.\""},{"time":499000,"text":"But there is a better translation."},{"time":501000,"text":"The Latin word \"cogito\""},{"time":503000,"text":"is derived from the prefix \"co,\" meaning \"together,\""},{"time":506000,"text":"and the verb \"agitare,\" meaning \"to shake.\""},{"time":509000,"text":"So, the original meaning of \"cogito\""},{"time":512000,"text":"is to shake together."},{"time":514000,"text":"And the proper translation of \"cogito ergo sum\""},{"time":517000,"text":"is \"I shake things up, therefore I am.\""},{"time":521000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":523000,"text":"Metaphor shakes things up,"},{"time":525000,"text":"giving us everything from Shakespeare to scientific discovery in the process."},{"time":530000,"text":"The mind is a plastic snow dome,"},{"time":533000,"text":"the most beautiful, most interesting,"},{"time":535000,"text":"and most itself, when, as Elvis put it,"},{"time":538000,"text":"it's all shook up."},{"time":540000,"text":"And metaphor keeps the mind shaking,"},{"time":542000,"text":"rattling and rolling, long after Elvis has left the building."},{"time":545000,"text":"Thank you very much."},{"time":547000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}